386→                        <div id="content">Let $A\subseteq \mathbb{N}$ be a finite set of size $N$. Is it true that, for any fixed $t$, there are\[\ll \frac{2^N}{N^{3/2}}\]many $S\subseteq A$ such that $\sum_{n\in S}n=t$?<br><br>If we further ask that $\lvert S\rvert=l$ (for any fixed $l$) then is the number of solutions\[\ll \frac{2^N}{N^2},\]with the implied constant independent of $l$ and $t$?</div>
387→                        <div id="problem_id"><a href="/362">#362</a>: <a href="#cite-Er65-362" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er65','362'); return false;">[Er65]</a><a href="#cite-Er73-362" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er73','362'); return false;">[Er73,p.129]</a><a href="#cite-ErGr80-362" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErGr80','362'); return false;">[ErGr80,p.59]</a></div>
388→                         
